Machine Learning Model - Estimating Voter Turnout

Data pre-processing

To utilize the ASEC data with the estimated new income amounts calculated under the microsimulation model, refactoring is required. The CPS voter supplement data, which we intend to utilize for the machine learning model, is structed differently from the ASEC data. Income is a categorical variable in the CPS and race, education, employment status, all utilize different labels for each category. As such, the code below refactors both the ASEC and CPS data to ensure they are structured the same to utilize in the machine learning model.

#' Calculating the total child tax credit benefit for families under the American Rescue Plan Act's expanded child tax credit
#'
#' @param hh_income Numeric total of family income in a year
#' @param marital_status Binary variable for if parents are married or not
#' @param old_children Numeric total number of children 6 - 18
#' @param young_children Numeric total number of children under age 6
#'
#' @return Numeric benefit in dollars
#'

arpa_tax_credit <- function(hh_income, marital_status, old_children, young_children){
  
  # Assumption: Maximum income for full benefit = $75,000 if one head of household OR $150,000 if married household
  
  mod_income <- 
    if_else(
      condition = marital_status == 1,
      true = pmax(hh_income - 150000, 0),
      false = pmax(hh_income - 75000, 0))
  
  # Benefit per child
  
  benefit <- 
    
    case_when(
      
      # Married couple, income < 400k, only older children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income < 400000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children == 0 ~ 
        pmax(2000, (3000 * old_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Married couple, income > 400k, only older children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income > 400000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children == 0 ~ 
        pmax(0, (3000 * old_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single household, income < 200k, only older children
      marital_status == 0 & hh_income < 200000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children == 0 ~
        pmax(2000, (3000 * old_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single household, income > 200k, only older children
      marital_status == 0 & hh_income > 200000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children == 0 ~ 
        pmax(0, (3000 * old_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Married couple, income < 400k, only young children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income < 400000 & old_children == 0 & young_children >= 1 ~ 
        pmax(2000, (3600 * young_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Married couple, income > 400k, only young children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income < 400000 & old_children == 0 & young_children >= 1 ~ 
        pmax(0, (3600 * young_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single household, income < 200k, only young children
      marital_status == 0 & hh_income < 200000 & old_children == 0 & young_children >= 1 ~ 
        pmax(2000, (3600 * young_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single household, income > 200k, only young children
      marital_status == 0 & hh_income > 200000 & old_children == 0 & young_children >= 1 ~ 
        pmax(0, (3600 * young_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Married couple, income < 400k, older and young children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income < 400000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children >= 1 ~
        pmax(2000, ((3000 * old_children) + (3600 * young_children)) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Married couple, income > 400k, older and young children
      marital_status == 1 & hh_income > 400000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children >= 1 ~
        pmax(0, ((3000 * old_children) + (3600 * young_children)) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single couple, income < 200k, older and young children
      marital_status == 0 & hh_income < 200000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children >= 1 ~
        pmax(2000, ((3000 * old_children) + (3600 * young_children)) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single couple, income > 200k, older and young children
      marital_status == 0  & hh_income > 200000 & old_children >= 1 & young_children >= 1 ~
        pmax(0, ((3000 * old_children) + (3600 * young_children)) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      TRUE ~ 0)
  
  return(benefit)
  
}

asec_arpa <-
  asec_2022 %>% 
  select(hh_income, marital_status, young_children, old_children)
  
arpa_credit <-
  asec_arpa %>%
  mutate(
    benefit = pmap_dbl(asec_arpa, arpa_tax_credit))

#' Calculating the total child tax credit benefit for families under the American Rescue Plan Act's expanded child tax credit
#'
#' @param hh_income Numeric total of family income in a year
#' @param marital_status Binary variable for if parents are married or not
#' @param tot_children Number of qualifying children
#'
#' @return Numeric benefit in dollars
#'

child_tax_credit <- function(hh_income, marital_status, tot_children){
  
  # Assumption: Maximum income for full benefit = $200,000 if one head of household OR $400,000 if married household
  
  mod_income <- 
    if_else(
      condition = marital_status == 1,
      true = pmax(hh_income - 400000, 0),
      false = pmax(hh_income - 200000, 0))
  
  # Benefit per child
  
  benefit <- 
    
    case_when(
      
      # Married couple
      marital_status == 1 ~ pmax(0, (2000 * tot_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      # Single household
      marital_status == 0 ~ pmax(0, (2000 * tot_children) - 0.05 * mod_income),
      
      TRUE ~ 0)
  
  return(benefit)
  
}

Pre-processing of ASEC data

Code 
# Appending ASEC data - adding benefit to total income for income estimated under microsimulation

asec_mod_inc <-
  
  bind_cols(
    asec_2022, 
    arpa_credit$benefit, 
    normal_ctc$benefit) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    arpa_benefit = ...15,
    ctc_reg = ...16) %>% 
  
  select(
    arpa_benefit,
    ctc_reg,
    hh_income) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    arpa_tot_inc = hh_income + arpa_benefit,
    ctc_reg_tot_inc = hh_income + ctc_reg) %>% 
  
  select(
    arpa_tot_inc,
    ctc_reg_tot_inc,
    - hh_income)
  
# Appending back to original data set 
asec_full <-
  bind_cols(
    asec_2022,
    asec_mod_inc)


# Refactoring ASEC to match CPS structure

asec_refactored <-
  
  asec_full %>% 
  
  rename(
    weight = ASECWTH) %>% 
  
  select(
    weight,
    age,
    sex,
    race,
    emp_status,
    education,
    marital_status,
    hh_income,
    arpa_tot_inc,
    ctc_reg_tot_inc) %>% 
  
  # Refactoring income 
  
  mutate(
    
    hh_income =
      case_when(
        hh_income < 5000 ~ 1,
        hh_income <= 7499 ~ 2,
        hh_income <= 9999 ~ 3,
        hh_income <= 12499 ~ 4,
        hh_income <= 14999 ~ 5,
        hh_income <= 19999 ~ 6,
        hh_income <= 24999 ~ 7,
        hh_income <= 29999 ~ 8, 
        hh_income <= 34999 ~ 9,
        hh_income <= 39999 ~ 10,
        hh_income <= 49999 ~ 11,
        hh_income <= 59999 ~ 12,
        hh_income <= 74999 ~ 13,
        hh_income <= 99999 ~ 14,
        hh_income <= 149999 ~ 15,
        hh_income >= 150000 ~ 16),
    
    arpa_tot_inc =
      case_when(
        arpa_tot_inc < 5000 ~ 1,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 7499 ~ 2,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 9999 ~ 3,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 12499 ~ 4,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 14999 ~ 5,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 19999 ~ 6,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 24999 ~ 7,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 29999 ~ 8, 
        arpa_tot_inc <= 34999 ~ 9,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 39999 ~ 10,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 49999 ~ 11,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 59999 ~ 12,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 74999 ~ 13,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 99999 ~ 14,
        arpa_tot_inc <= 149999 ~ 15,
        arpa_tot_inc >= 150000 ~ 16),
    
    ctc_reg_tot_inc =
      case_when(
        ctc_reg_tot_inc < 5000 ~ 1,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 7499 ~ 2,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 9999 ~ 3,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 12499 ~ 4,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 14999 ~ 5,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 19999 ~ 6,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 24999 ~ 7,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 29999 ~ 8, 
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 34999 ~ 9,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 39999 ~ 10,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 49999 ~ 11,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 59999 ~ 12,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 74999 ~ 13,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 99999 ~ 14,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc <= 149999 ~ 15,
        ctc_reg_tot_inc >= 150000 ~ 16)) %>% 
  
  # Refactoring education (1 = no hs degree, 2 = hs diploma, 3 = some college,
  # 4 = bachelor's, 5 = higher degree)
  
  mutate(
    education = 
      case_when(
        education <= 072 ~ 1,
        education == 73 ~ 2,
        education <= 110 ~ 3,
        education <= 122 ~ 4,
        education <= 125 ~ 5)) %>% 
  
  # Refactoring race (1 = White, 2 = Black, 3 = American indian, 4 = Asian, 5 = 2 or more races and other)
  
  mutate(
    race = 
      case_when(
        race == 100 ~ 1,
        race == 200 ~ 2,
        race == 300 ~ 3,
        race == 650 ~ 4,
        race == 651 ~ 4,
        race == 652 ~ 4, 
        race > 660 ~ 5)) %>% 
  
  # Refactoring employment (1 = employed, 2 = unemployed)
  
  mutate(
    emp_status =
      case_when(
        emp_status == 01 ~ 1,
        emp_status == 02 ~ 1,
        emp_status == 10 ~ 1,
        emp_status == 12 ~ 1,
        emp_status <= 36 ~ 0))

Pre-processing of CPS data

Code 
cps <- read_csv(here("data/cps_supp.csv")) %>% 
  
  select(
    PWSSWGT,
    PRTAGE,
    PEEDUCA,
    PEMARITL,
    PESEX,
    PEMLR,
    PTDTRACE,
    HEFAMINC,
    PES2,
    PES1) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    weight = PWSSWGT,
    education = PEEDUCA,
    age = PRTAGE,
    marital_status = PEMARITL,
    sex = PESEX,
    emp_status = PEMLR,
    race = PTDTRACE,
    hh_income = HEFAMINC,
    voted = PES1) %>%
  
  filter(
    !education == -1,
    !age < 0,
    !marital_status == -1,
    !emp_status == -1,
    !race == -1,
    !hh_income == -1,
    !voted < 0) %>% 
  
  select(
    weight,
    age,
    sex,
    race,
    education,
    marital_status,
    emp_status,
    hh_income,
    voted) %>% 
  
   # Refactoring education (1 = no hs degree, 2 = hs diploma, 3 = some college, # 4 = bachelor's, 5 = higher degree)
  
  mutate(
    education = 
      case_when(
        education <= 38 ~ 1,
        education == 39 ~ 2,
        education <= 42 ~ 3,
        education == 43 ~ 4,
        education <= 46 ~ 5)) %>% 

  # Refactoring race (1 = White, 2 = Black, 3 = American indian, 4 = Asian, 5 = 2 or more races and other)
  
  mutate(
    race = 
      case_when(
        race == 01 ~ 1,
        race == 02 ~ 2,
        race == 03 ~ 3,
        race == 04 ~ 4,
        race == 05 ~ 4,
        race <= 26 ~ 5)) %>% 
  
  # Refactoring employment (1 = employed, 2 = unemployed)
  
  mutate(
    emp_status =
      case_when(
        emp_status == 1 ~ 1,
        emp_status == 2 ~ 1,
        emp_status <= 7 ~ 0))

Exploratory Data Analysis - Voter turnout rate by Income Level

*Weights have been applied*

Code 
cps <-
  cps %>% 
  mutate(voted = as.factor(voted))

# Voter turnout rate by income level

cps_voted <-
  
  cps %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = 
      case_when(
        hh_income <= 7 ~ "$25,000 or less",
        hh_income <= 11 ~ "$25,000 - $50,000",
        hh_income <= 13 ~ "$50,000 - $75,000",
        hh_income == 14 ~ "$75,000 - $100,000",
        hh_income <= 16 ~ "$150,000 +")) %>%
  
  filter(voted == 1) %>% 
  
  summarize(
    total = sum(weight),
    .by = c(inc_grouped)) %>% 
  
  mutate(voted = "voted")

cps_no_voted <-
   
  cps %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = 
      case_when(
        hh_income <= 7 ~ "$25,000 or less",
        hh_income <= 11 ~ "$25,000 - $50,000",
        hh_income <= 13 ~ "$50,000 - $75,000",
        hh_income == 14 ~ "$75,000 - $100,000",
        hh_income <= 16 ~ "$150,000 +")) %>%
  
    filter(voted == 2) %>% 

  summarize(
    total = sum(weight),
    .by = c(inc_grouped)) %>% 
  
  mutate(voted = "no vote")

cps_turnout <-
  bind_rows(
    cps_voted,
    cps_no_voted) %>% 
 
  arrange(inc_grouped) %>% 
  
  pivot_wider(
    values_from = total,
    names_from = voted) %>% 
  
  rename(
    voted = "voted",
    no_vote = `no vote`) %>% 
  
  select(
    inc_grouped,
    voted,
    no_vote) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    total_pop = voted + no_vote,
    turnout_rate = voted / total_pop) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = fct_reorder(inc_grouped, turnout_rate, .desc = FALSE))

cps_turnout %>% 
  
  ggplot() +
  
  geom_col(
    aes(
      x = inc_grouped, 
      y = turnout_rate),
     fill = "#add8e6") +
  
  geom_text(
    aes(x = inc_grouped,
        y = turnout_rate,
        label = round(turnout_rate, digits = 3))) +

  labs(
    title = "Voter Turnout Rate by Income Level",
    x = "Income Level",
    y = "Voter Turnout Rate") +
  
  theme_classic()

Machine Learning Model(s)

Machine Learning - MODEL ONE: Logistic Regression Model

We first utilize logistic regression as a model to predict voter turnout rate utilizing predictors of age, sex, race, educational attainment, and employment status. We train the model on the CPS data with the CPS income levels.

Under the first model, the following metrics are collected:

  • Accuracy: 71.6%

    • This is the proportion of correct predictions compared to all predictions made by the model.Â 

  • Precision: 73.7%

    • This is the proportion of the sample the model correctly identified as having voted out of those who actually voted.

  • Recall: 86.1%

    • This is the proportion of correctly identified voters.Â 
Code 
# Logistic regression recipe
logistic_recipe <- 
  recipe(voted ~ ., data = cps) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_rm(weight)

# Logistic regression model specification
logistic_model <- 
  logistic_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("glm") %>% 
  set_mode("classification")

# Workflow
logistic_wf <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(logistic_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(logistic_model)

# Cross-validation on the training set
folds <- 
  vfold_cv(cps, v = 5, repeats = 2)

# Fit the model using cross-validation on the training set
logistic_resamples <- 
  logistic_wf %>% 
  fit_resamples(folds)

# Collect and check cross-validation results
logistic_resamples %>% 
  collect_metrics()

Code 
# Finalizing model 
logistic_best <-
  logistic_resamples %>% 
  select_best(metric = "accuracy")

# Final model selection
logistic_final_fit <-
  logistic_model %>% 
  finalize_model(logistic_best)

# Final work flow
logistic_final_wf <-
  workflow() %>% 
  add_recipe(logistic_recipe) %>% 
  add_model(logistic_final_fit)

# Fitting best model
logistic_final <-
  logistic_final_wf %>% 
  fit(data = cps)

# Model predictions
logistic_predictions <-
  bind_cols(
    cps,
    predict(
      object = logistic_final,
      new_data = cps))

Machine Learning - MODEL Two: Random Forest Model

We next utilize random forest as a model to predict voter turnout rate utilizing predictors of age, sex, race, educational attainment, and employment status. We train the model on the CPS data with the CPS income levels.

Under the second model, the following metrics are collected:

  • Accuracy: 75.2%

    • This is the proportion of correct predictions compared to all predictions made by the model.Â 

  • Precision: 76.5%

    • This is the proportion of the sample the model correctly identified as having voted out of those who actually voted.

  • Recall: 88.3%

    • This is the proportion of correctly identified voters.Â 
Code 
# Random Forest recipe
rf_recipe <-
  recipe(voted ~ ., data = cps) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_rm(weight)

# Random Forest model specification
rf_model <-
  rand_forest(
    trees = 1000,
    mtry = 2,
    min_n = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity")

# Random Forest workflow
rf_wf <-
  workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(rf_recipe) %>%
  add_model(rf_model)

# Cross-validation setup
folds_rf <-
  vfold_cv(cps, v = 3)

# Tuning grid
rf_grid <-
  grid_regular(
    min_n(range = c(1, 25)),
    levels = 3)

# Tuning the model
rf_resamples <-
  tune_grid(
    rf_wf,
    resamples = folds_rf,
    grid = rf_grid)

# Selecting the best model
rf_best <-
  rf_resamples %>%
  select_best(metric = "accuracy")

# Finalizing the model
rf_final <-
  rf_model %>%
  finalize_model(rf_best)

# Fit the best Random Forest model
rf_final_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe(rf_recipe) %>%
  add_model(rf_final)

rf_fit <- rf_final_wf %>%
  fit(data = cps)

# Make predictions on CPS data
cps_predictions <- predict(rf_fit, new_data = cps)

# Bind predictions to CPS data and evaluate results
cps_results <- bind_cols(cps, cps_predictions)

# Assuming `voted` is the outcome column in CPS data
confusion_matrix_rf <- conf_mat(cps_results, truth = voted, estimate = .pred_class)

Random Forest Variable Importance Plot

The variable importance plot suggests that the most important predictor in predicting whether or not someone voted is age. Additionally, the plot indicates that household income plays a relatively medium role in predicting whether or not a person voted among the individuals in the sample.

Fitting the Model

Given that the random forest model had higher rates of accuracy, precision, and recall than the logistic regression model, we utilize the random forest model to fit the testing data. We fit the model on the testing data with income estimated from the microsimulation model under each of the policies. The first fit of the model is using income values estimated under the ARPA CTC policy. The second fit of the model is using income values estimated under the normal CTC policy.

Random Forest Testing - ASEC Individual Data (ARPA CTC Estimated Income)

Estimated Federal Voter Turnout Rate

*Weights have been applied*

Utilizing the random forest model to predict the federal voter turnout rate with incomes under the ARPA expanded child tax credit policy, we estimate a turnout rate of 78.6%.

arpa_no_voted <-
  arpa_vote_predictions %>% 
  filter(.pred_class == 2) %>% 
  summarize(

arpa_turnout <-
  bind_rows(
    arpa_voted,
    arpa_no_voted) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = voted,
    values_from = total) %>% 
  rename(no_vote = `no vote`) %>% 
   summarize(

Estimated Federal Voter Turnout Rate Under Each Policy

*Weights have been applied *

Utilizing the random forest model to predict the federal voter turnout rate under income levels without any child tax credit policy, we estimate a turnout rate of 62.5%.

The plot below summarizes the estimated federal voter turnout rate with incomes under each policy. We find, as expected, that the turnout rate is the highest when individuals receive the expanded child tax credit under ARPA, however, the difference in the estimated federal voter turnout rate between the normal CTC and ARPA CTC is very small, suggesting that the while the expansion had an impact on the average income of individuals, it may not have had a very noticeable impact on voter turnout.

Estimated Federal Voter Turnout Rate by Income Group Under Each Policy

*Weights have been applied *

The plots below show the estimated voter turnout rates by income group under each policy. The table below also reflects this and calculates the difference in voter turnout rate by income level under each policy.

We estimate that overall, under both child tax credit policies, voter turnout rates are expected to increase across all income groups. We estimate the highest increase in voter turnout rates among the wealthiest income group. For the lowest income group, we also estimate a substantial increase in voter turnout under both policies, though, this increase is not as much as the wealthiest income category.

Code 
# Voter turnout rate by income level - ARPA

arpa_inc_voted <-
  
  arpa_vote_predictions %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = 
      case_when(
        hh_income <= 7 ~ "$25,000 or less",
        hh_income <= 11 ~ "$25,000 - $50,000",
        hh_income <= 13 ~ "$50,000 - $75,000",
        hh_income == 14 ~ "$75,000 - $100,000",
        hh_income <= 16 ~ "$150,000 +")) %>%
  
  filter(.pred_class == 1) %>% 
  
  summarize(
    total = sum(weight),
    .by = c(inc_grouped)) %>% 
  
  mutate(voted = "voted")

arpa_inc_nv <-
   
  arpa_vote_predictions %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = 
      case_when(
        hh_income <= 7 ~ "$25,000 or less",
        hh_income <= 11 ~ "$25,000 - $50,000",
        hh_income <= 13 ~ "$50,000 - $75,000",
        hh_income == 14 ~ "$75,000 - $100,000",
        hh_income <= 16 ~ "$150,000 +")) %>%
  
    filter(.pred_class == 2) %>% 

  summarize(
    total = sum(weight),
    .by = c(inc_grouped)) %>% 
  
  mutate(voted = "no vote")

arpa_inc_turnout <-
  
  bind_rows(
    arpa_inc_voted,
    arpa_inc_nv) %>% 
 
  arrange(inc_grouped) %>% 
  
  pivot_wider(
    values_from = total,
    names_from = voted) %>% 
  
  rename(
    voted = "voted",
    no_vote = `no vote`) %>% 
  
  select(
    inc_grouped,
    voted,
    no_vote) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    total_pop = voted + no_vote,
    turnout_rate = voted / total_pop) %>% 
  
  mutate(
    inc_grouped = fct_reorder(inc_grouped, turnout_rate, .desc = FALSE)) %>% 
  mutate(
    policy = "arpa_ctc")
